work alongside humans"],[0,[],0,", like co-workers."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"This is particularly prevalent, write the Penn State researchers in "],[0,[10],1,"their study"],[0,[],0," published in the journal "],[0,[5],1,"Automation in Construction"],[0,[],0," this April, in fields like construction where thereâs little opportunity for robotic workers and human workers to work separately from one another. To accomplish dynamic tasks, like laying brick, itâs more likely that human workers and robots will have to work together."]]],[1,"aside",[[0,[],0,"âI believe our proposed technology might be powerful for the future.â"]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"But this is much easier said than done says Jebelli, especially because building trust between humans and robots can be a difficult task. "]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"âWhen it comes to human-robot collaboration, building that trust, and even providing [HRC] training for the workers is very important,â says Jebelli. Otherwise, it can be easy to misinterpret the intentions of your robot companion, he explains."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Human workers may get annoyed at each other when a task goes south, but this is amplified if their co-worker is a robot because thereâs little opportunity to understand or discuss why different choices were made, e.g. speeding through a detail-oriented task."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Creating a âhuman-in-the-loopâ system for these robots that can help them better understand and meet the needs of their human co-workers will be essential to building this trust, says Jebelli. And thatâs exactly what they set out to do when they stuck an EEG cap inside a bunch of hardhats a let participants loose with a team of robot workers."]]],[10,1],[1,"p",[[0,[11],1,"HOW DOES IT ACTUALLY WORK?"]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"The Penn State team developed an HRC framework that used EEG data collected from participants as input for robots to help them interpret the cognitive load of their human coworkers."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"The framework worked like this:"]]],[3,"ul",[[[0,[],0,"EEG data was collected via the lined hard hats and then digitally âcleanedâ of excess electrical noise (e.g. eye blinking or nearby electronics) explains "],[0,[12],1,"Yizhi Liu"],[0,[],0,", the studyâs first author and a Penn State doctoral student"]],[[0,[],0,"A machine-learning algorithm then processed the data to find distinct stress patterns"]],[[0,[],0,"These patterns were then characterized when the worker had an increased, decreased, or steady cognitive load"]],[[0,[],0,"The robot would then react accordingly, either slowing down, speeding up, or keeping its pace steady to accommodate for the worker"]]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"One interesting problem to overcome for this team was how to separate general stress from work stress to ensure the robot was receiving up-to-date cognitive load information. To account for this, Jebelli says they first established baseline EEG stress levels by having the participants wear the EEG-lined hardhats for a few minutes at the beginning of the trial."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"âFor example, assume I had a bad weekend... like I got a rejection for one of my proposals or something like that,â says Jebelli. âWhen I go to the job site, this will be added to the daily stress. This is something that our framework will consider.â"]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"In the case of the brick-laying robot analyzed in the study, the robot can use this information to adjust its pace accordingly, explains a co-author on the student and Penn State post-doctoral scholar, "],[0,[13],1,"Mahmoud Habibnezhad"],[0,[],0,"."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"âWhen the robot changes its performance the worker understands [why],â says Habibnezhad. âThe worker [can] understand that this robot is slowing down because heâs tired ... That instills trust over time.â"]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"The authors write that this approach had over an 80 percent accuracy rate when it came to appropriately making these corrections."]]],[1,